# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hierholzer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] In graph theory, a **cycle** in a graph is a non-empty trail in which only the first and last vertices are equal.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] A **directed cycle** in a directed graph is a non-empty directed trail in which only the first and last vertices are equal.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] A graph without cycles is called an *acyclic graph*.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] A directed graph without directed cycles is called a *directed acyclic graph*.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] A connected graph without cycles is called a *tree*.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] A chordless cycle in a graph, also called a hole or an induced cycle, is a cycle such that no two vertices of the cycle are connected by an edge that does not itself belong to the cycle.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] An antihole is the complement of a graph hole.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] Chordless cycles may be used to characterize perfect graphs: by the strong perfect graph theorem, a graph is perfect if and only if none of its holes or antiholes have an odd number of vertices that is greater than three.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] A chordal graph, a special type of perfect graph, has no holes of any size greater than three.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] The girth of a graph is the length of its shortest cycle; this cycle is necessarily chordless.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] Cages are defined as the smallest regular graphs with given combinations of degree and girth.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] A peripheral cycle is a cycle in a graph with the property that every two edges not on the cycle can be connected by a path whose interior vertices avoid the cycle.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] In a graph that is not formed by adding one edge to a cycle, a peripheral cycle must be an induced cycle.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] The term *cycle* may also refer to an element of the cycle space of a graph.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] There are many cycle spaces, one for each coefficient field or ring.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] The most common is the *binary cycle space* (usually called simply the *cycle space*), which consists of the edge sets that have even degree at every vertex; it forms a vector space over the two-element field.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] By Veblen's theorem, every element of the cycle space may be formed as an edge-disjoint union of simple cycles.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] A cycle basis of the graph is a set of simple cycles that forms a basis of the cycle space.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] Using ideas from algebraic topology, the binary cycle space generalizes to vector spaces or modules over other rings such as the integers, rational or real numbers, etc.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] The existence of a cycle in directed and undirected graphs can be determined by whether a depth-first search (DFS) finds an edge that points to an ancestor of the current vertex (i.e., it contains a back edge).
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] All the back edges which DFS skips over are part of cycles.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] In an undirected graph, the edge to the parent of a node should not be counted as a back edge, but finding any other already visited vertex will indicate a back edge.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] In the case of undirected graphs, only *O*(*n*) time is required to find a cycle in an *n*-vertex graph, since at most *n* − 1 edges can be tree edges.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] Many topological sorting algorithms will detect cycles too, since those are obstacles for topological order to exist.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] Also, if a directed graph has been divided into strongly connected components, cycles only exist within the components and not between them, since cycles are strongly connected.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] For directed graphs, distributed message-based algorithms can be used.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] These algorithms rely on the idea that a message sent by a vertex in a cycle will come back to itself.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] Distributed cycle detection algorithms are useful for processing large-scale graphs using a distributed graph processing system on a computer cluster (or supercomputer).
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] Applications of cycle detection include the use of wait-for graphs to detect deadlocks in concurrent systems.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] For undirected graphs, "neighbour" means all vertices connected to *v*, except for the one that recursively called *DFS(v)*.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] This omission prevents the algorithm from finding a trivial cycle of the form *v*→*w*→*v*; these exist in every undirected graph with at least one edge.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] A variant using breadth-first search instead will find a cycle of the smallest possible length.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] The corresponding characterization for the existence of a closed walk visiting each edge exactly once in a directed graph is that the graph be strongly connected and have equal numbers of incoming and outgoing edges at each vertex.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] In either case, the resulting closed trail is known as an Eulerian trail.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] If a finite undirected graph has even degree at each of its vertices, regardless of whether it is connected, then it is possible to find a set of simple cycles that together cover each edge exactly once: this is Veblen's theorem.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] When a connected graph does not meet the conditions of Euler's theorem, a closed walk of minimum length covering each edge at least once can nevertheless be found in polynomial time by solving the route inspection problem.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] The problem of finding a single simple cycle that covers each vertex exactly once, rather than covering the edges, is much harder.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] Such a cycle is known as a Hamiltonian cycle, and determining whether it exists is NP-complete.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] The cycle double cover conjecture states that, for every bridgeless graph, there exists a multiset of simple cycles that covers each edge of the graph exactly twice.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] Proving that this is true (or finding a counterexample) remains an open problem.
[src:hierholzer/cycle-graph-theory] Several important classes of graphs can be defined by or characterized by their cycles.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] In combinatorial mathematics, a **de Bruijn sequence** of order *n* on a size-*k* alphabet *A* is a cyclic sequence in which every possible length-*n* string on *A* occurs exactly once as a substring (i.e., as a *contiguous* subsequence).
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] Such a sequence is denoted by *B*(*k*, *n*) and has length *k**n*, which is also the number of distinct strings of length *n* on *A*.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] Each of these distinct strings, when taken as a substring of *B*(*k*, *n*), must start at a different position, because substrings starting at the same position are not distinct.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] Therefore, *B*(*k*, *n*) must have *at least* *k**n* symbols.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] And since *B*(*k*, *n*) has *exactly* *k**n* symbols, de Bruijn sequences are optimally short with respect to the property of containing every string of length *n* at least once.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] The sequences are named after the Dutch mathematician Nicolaas Govert de Bruijn, who wrote about them in 1946.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] As he later wrote, the existence of de Bruijn sequences for each order together with the above properties were first proved, for the case of alphabets with two elements, by Camille Flye Sainte-Marie (1894).
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] The generalization to larger alphabets is due to Tatyana van Aardenne-Ehrenfest and de Bruijn (1951).
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] Automata for recognizing these sequences are denoted as de Bruijn automata.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] The earliest known example of a de Bruijn sequence comes from Sanskrit prosody where, since the work of Pingala, each possible three-syllable pattern of long and short syllables is given a name, such as 'y' for short–long–long and 'm' for long–long–long.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] To remember these names, the mnemonic *yamātārājabhānasalagām* is used, in which each three-syllable pattern occurs starting at its name: 'yamātā' has a short–long–long pattern, 'mātārā' has a long–long–long pattern, and so on, until 'salagām' which has a short–short–long pattern.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] This mnemonic, equivalent to a de Bruijn sequence on binary 3-tuples, is of unknown antiquity, but is at least as old as Charles Philip Brown's 1869 book on Sanskrit prosody that mentions it and considers it "an ancient line, written by Pāṇini".
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] In 1894, A. de Rivière raised the question in an issue of the French problem journal *L'Intermédiaire des Mathématiciens*, of the existence of a circular arrangement of zeroes and ones of size $2^{n}$ that contains all $2^{n}$ binary sequences of length n .
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] The problem was solved (in the affirmative), along with the count of $2^{2^{n-1}-n}$ distinct solutions, by Camille Flye Sainte-Marie in the same year.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] This was largely forgotten, and Martin (1934) proved the existence of such cycles for general alphabet size in place of 2, with an algorithm for constructing them.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] Finally, when in 1944 Kees Posthumus conjectured the count $2^{2^{n-1}-n}$ for binary sequences, de Bruijn proved the conjecture in 1946, through which the problem became well known.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] Karl Popper independently describes these objects in his *The Logic of Scientific Discovery* (1934), calling them "shortest random-like sequences".
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] The de Bruijn sequences can be constructed by taking a Hamiltonian path of an *n*-dimensional de Bruijn graph over *k* symbols (or equivalently, an Eulerian cycle of an (*n* − 1)-dimensional de Bruijn graph).
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] An alternative construction involves concatenating together, in lexicographic order, all the Lyndon words whose length divides *n*.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] An inverse Burrows–Wheeler transform can be used to generate the required Lyndon words in lexicographic order.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] de Bruijn sequences can also be constructed using shift registers or via finite fields.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] Goal: to construct a *B*(2, 4) de Bruijn sequence of length 24 = 16 using Eulerian (*n* − 1 = 4 − 1 = 3) 3-D de Bruijn graph cycle.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] Each edge in this 3-dimensional de Bruijn graph corresponds to a sequence of four digits: the three digits that label the vertex that the edge is leaving followed by the one that labels the edge.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] If one traverses the edge labeled 1 from 000, one arrives at 001, thereby indicating the presence of the subsequence 0001 in the de Bruijn sequence.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] To traverse each edge exactly once is to use each of the 16 four-digit sequences exactly once.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] ...and then we return to the starting point.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] Each of the eight 3-digit sequences (corresponding to the eight vertices) appears exactly twice, and each of the sixteen 4-digit sequences (corresponding to the 16 edges) appears exactly once.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] Mathematically, an inverse Burrows—Wheeler transform on a word w generates a multi-set of equivalence classes consisting of strings and their rotations.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] These equivalence classes of strings each contain a Lyndon word as a unique minimum element, so the inverse Burrows—Wheeler transform can be considered to generate a set of Lyndon words.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] It follows that arranging these Lyndon words in lexicographic order will yield a de Bruijn sequence *B*(*k*,*n*), and that this will be the first de Bruijn sequence in lexicographic order.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] Position the string w′ above the string w, and map each letter's position in w′ to its position in w while preserving order.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] This process defines the Standard Permutation.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] Write this permutation in cycle notation with the smallest position in each cycle first, and the cycles sorted in increasing order.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] For each cycle, replace each number with the corresponding letter from string w′ in that position.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] Each cycle has now become a Lyndon word, and they are arranged in lexicographic order, so dropping the parentheses yields the first de Bruijn sequence.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] For example, to construct the smallest *B*(2,4) de Bruijn sequence of length 24 = 16, repeat the alphabet (ab) 8 times yielding *w*=abababababababab.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] Sort the characters in w, yielding *w′*=aaaaaaaabbbbbbbb.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] Position w′ above w as shown, and map each element in w′ to the corresponding element in w by drawing a line.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] Then, replacing each number by the corresponding letter in w′ from that column yields: (a)(aaab)(aabb)(ab)(abbb)(b).
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] These are all of the Lyndon words whose length divides 4, in lexicographic order, so dropping the parentheses gives *B*(2,4) = aaaabaabbababbbb.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] The following Python code calculates a de Bruijn sequence, given *k* and *n*, based on an algorithm from Frank Ruskey's *Combinatorial Generation*.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] Note that these sequences are understood to "wrap around" in a cycle.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] For example, the first sequence contains 110 and 100 in this fashion.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] de Bruijn cycles are of general use in neuroscience and psychology experiments that examine the effect of stimulus order upon neural systems, and can be specially crafted for use with functional magnetic resonance imaging.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] The symbols of a de Bruijn sequence written around a circular object (such as a wheel of a robot) can be used to identify its angle by examining the *n* consecutive symbols facing a fixed point.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] This angle-encoding problem is known as the "rotating drum problem".
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] Gray codes can be used as similar rotary positional encoding mechanisms, a method commonly found in rotary encoders.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] A de Bruijn sequence can be used to quickly find the index of the least significant set bit ("right-most 1") or the most significant set bit ("left-most 1") in a word using bitwise operations and multiplication.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] The `lowestBitIndex()` function returns the index of the least-significant set bit in *v*, or zero if *v* has no set bits.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] The operation `(v & -v)` zeros all bits except the least-significant bit set, resulting in a new value which is a power of 2.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] This power of 2 is multiplied (arithmetic modulo 232) by the de Bruijn sequence, thus producing a 32-bit product in which the bit sequence of the 5 MSBs is unique for each power of 2.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] The 5 MSBs are shifted into the LSB positions to produce a hash code in the range [0, 31], which is then used as an index into hash table BitPositionLookup.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] The selected hash table value is the bit index of the least significant set bit in *v*.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] In the above example an alternative de Bruijn sequence (0x06EB14F9U) is used, with corresponding reordering of array values.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] The choice of this particular de Bruijn sequence is arbitrary, but the hash table values must be ordered to match the chosen de Bruijn sequence.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] The `keepHighestBit()` function zeros all bits except the most-significant set bit, resulting in a value which is a power of 2, which is then processed as in the previous example.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] A de Bruijn sequence can be used to shorten a brute-force attack on a PIN-like code lock that does not have an "enter" key and accepts the last *n* digits entered.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] For example, a digital door lock with a 4-digit code (each digit having 10 possibilities, from 0 to 9) would have *B* (10, 4) solutions, with length 10000.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] Therefore, only at most 10000 + 3 = 10003 (as the solutions are cyclic) presses are needed to open the lock, whereas trying all codes separately would require 4 × 10000 = 40000 presses.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] Multi de Bruijn sequence: a cyclic or linear sequence that contains every k-mer over an alphabet of size q exactly m times .
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] For example, over the binary alphabet {0, 1}, the cyclic sequence (00010111) and the linear sequence 000101110 each contain two instances of each 2-mer 00, 01, 10, 11.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] There are two sequences for multiplicity m=2, alphabet size q = 2, and word size k=1: (0011), and (0101), and 5 for k=2.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] A de Bruijn torus is a toroidal array with the property that every *k*-ary *m*-by-*n* matrix occurs exactly once.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] Such a pattern can be used for two-dimensional positional encoding in a fashion analogous to that described above for rotary encoding.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] Position can be determined by examining the *m*-by-*n* matrix directly adjacent to the sensor, and calculating its position on the de Bruijn torus.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] Computing the position of a particular unique tuple or matrix in a de Bruijn sequence or torus is known as the *de Bruijn decoding problem*.
[src:hierholzer/de-bruijn-sequence] Efficient ⁠ $\color {Blue}O(n\log n)$ ⁠ decoding algorithms exist for special, recursively constructed sequences and extend to the two-dimensional case. de Bruijn decoding is of interest, e.g., in cases where large sequences or tori are used for positional encoding.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] In graph theory, an **Eulerian trail** (or **Eulerian path**) is a trail in a finite graph that visits every edge exactly once (allowing for revisiting vertices).
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] Similarly, an **Eulerian circuit** or **Eulerian cycle** is an Eulerian trail that starts and ends on the same vertex.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] They were first discussed by Leonhard Euler while solving the famous Seven Bridges of Königsberg problem in 1736.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] ; i.e., a path starting and ending on the same vertex) that visits each edge exactly once?
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] Euler proved that a necessary condition for the existence of Eulerian circuits is that all vertices in the graph have an even degree, and stated without proof that connected graphs with all vertices of even degree have an Eulerian circuit.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] The first complete proof of this latter claim was published posthumously in 1873 by Carl Hierholzer.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] every vertex has an even number of incident edges.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] The term **Eulerian graph** has two common meanings in graph theory.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] One meaning is a graph with an Eulerian circuit, and the other is a graph with every vertex of even degree.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] These definitions coincide for connected graphs.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] For the existence of Eulerian trails it is necessary that zero or two vertices have an odd degree; this means the Königsberg graph is *not* Eulerian.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] If there are no vertices of odd degree, all Eulerian trails are circuits.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] If there are exactly two vertices of odd degree, all Eulerian trails start at one of them and end at the other.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] A graph that has an Eulerian trail but not an Eulerian circuit is called **semi-Eulerian**.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] An **Eulerian trail**, or **Euler walk**, in an undirected graph is a walk that uses each edge exactly once.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] If such a walk exists, the graph is called **traversable** or **semi-eulerian**.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] An **Eulerian cycle**, also called an **Eulerian circuit** or **Euler tour**, in an undirected graph is a circuit that uses each edge exactly once.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] If such a cycle exists, the graph is called **Eulerian** or **unicursal**.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] The term "Eulerian graph" is also sometimes used in a weaker sense to denote a graph where every vertex has even degree.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] For finite connected graphs the two definitions are equivalent, while a possibly unconnected graph is Eulerian in the weaker sense if and only if each connected component has an Eulerian cycle.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] For directed graphs, "path" has to be replaced with *directed path* and "cycle" with *directed cycle*.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] The definition and properties of Eulerian trails, cycles and graphs are valid for multigraphs as well.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] An **Eulerian orientation** of an undirected graph *G* is an assignment of a direction to each edge of *G* such that, at each vertex *v*, the indegree of *v* equals the outdegree of *v*.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] Such an orientation exists for any undirected graph in which every vertex has even degree, and may be found by constructing an Euler tour in each connected component of *G* and then orienting the edges according to the tour.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] Every Eulerian orientation of a connected graph is a strong orientation, an orientation that makes the resulting directed graph strongly connected.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] While the *graph traversal* in Fleury's algorithm is linear in the number of edges, i.e. $O(|E|)$ , we also need to factor in the complexity of detecting bridges.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] If we are to re-run Tarjan's linear time bridge-finding algorithm after the removal of every edge, Fleury's algorithm will have a time complexity of $O(|E|^{2})$ .
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] A dynamic bridge-finding algorithm of Thorup (2000) allows this to be improved to $O(|E|\cdot \log ^{3}|E|\cdot \log \log |E|)$ , but this is still significantly slower than alternative algorithms.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] This algorithm may also be implemented with a deque.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] Because it is only possible to get stuck when the deque represents a closed tour, one should rotate the deque by removing edges from the tail and adding them to the head until unstuck, and then continue until all edges are accounted for.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] The number of Eulerian circuits in a *directed graph* can be calculated using the so-called **BEST theorem**, named after de **B**ruijn, van Aardenne-**E**hrenfest, **S**mith and **T**utte.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] The formula states that the number of Eulerian circuits in a digraph is the product of certain degree factorials and the number of rooted arborescences.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] The latter can be computed as a determinant, by the matrix tree theorem, giving a polynomial time algorithm.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] BEST theorem is first stated in this form in a "note added in proof" to the Aardenne-Ehrenfest and de Bruijn paper (1951).
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] The original proof was bijective and generalized the de Bruijn sequences.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] It is a variation on an earlier result by Smith and Tutte (1941).
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] Counting the number of Eulerian circuits on *undirected graphs* is much more difficult.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] This problem is known to be #P-complete.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] A similar formula was later obtained by M.I.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] Eulerian trails are used in bioinformatics to reconstruct the DNA sequence from its fragments.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] They are also used in CMOS circuit design to find an optimal logic gate ordering.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] There are some algorithms for processing trees that rely on an Euler tour of the tree (where each edge is treated as a pair of arcs).
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] The de Bruijn sequences can be constructed as Eulerian trails of de Bruijn graphs.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] In an infinite graph, the corresponding concept to an Eulerian trail or Eulerian cycle is an Eulerian line, a doubly-infinite trail that covers all of the edges of the graph.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] It is not sufficient for the existence of such a trail that the graph be connected and that all vertex degrees be even; for instance, the infinite Cayley graph shown, with all vertex degrees equal to four, has no Eulerian line.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] The infinite graphs that contain Eulerian lines were characterized by Erdős, Grünwald & Weiszfeld (1936).
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] Euler stated a necessary condition for a finite graph to be Eulerian as all vertices must have even degree.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] Hierholzer proved this is a sufficient condition in a paper published in 1873.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] This leads to the following necessary and sufficient statement for what a finite graph must have to be Eulerian: An undirected connected finite graph is Eulerian if and only if every vertex of G has even degree.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] The following result was proved by Veblen in 1912: An undirected connected graph is Eulerian if and only if it is the disjoint union of some cycles.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] Hierholzer developed a linear time algorithm for constructing an Eulerian tour in an undirected graph.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] It is possible to have a directed graph that has all even out-degrees but is not Eulerian.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] Since an Eulerian circuit leaves a vertex the same number of times as it enters that vertex, a necessary condition for an Eulerian circuit to exist is that the in-degree and out-degree are equal at each vertex.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] Obviously, connectivity is also necessary.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] König proved that these conditions are also sufficient.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] That is, a directed graph is Eulerian if and only if it is connected and the in-degree and out-degree are equal at each vertex.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] In this theorem it doesn't matter whether "connected" means "weakly connected" or "strongly connected" since they are equivalent for Eulerian graphs.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] Hierholzer's linear time algorithm for constructing an Eulerian tour is also applicable to directed graphs.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] All mixed graphs that are both even and symmetric are guaranteed to be Eulerian.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] However, this is not a necessary condition, as it is possible to construct a non-symmetric, even graph that is Eulerian.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] The process of checking if a mixed graph is Eulerian is harder than checking if an undirected or directed graph is Eulerian because the balanced set condition concerns every possible subset of vertices.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] Define an **Eulerian graph** as a graph with an Eulerian cycle.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] Every Eulerian graph is a bridgeless graph.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] This is because in an Eulerian graph every edge is a part of an Eulerian cycle.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] Hence, if the edge is deleted, then its endpoints remain connected through the rest of the cycle.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] Define an **almost Eulerian graph** as a graph that can be made Eulerian by adding a single edge (equivalently, a graph that contains an Eulerian trail).
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] Every almost-Eulerian graph is almost-bridgeless, but the opposite is not true.
[src:hierholzer/eulerian-path] The classes of bridgeless graphs and almost-Eulerian graphs have a non-empty intersection (the Eulerian graphs are both bridgeless and almost-Eulerian), but they do not contain each other.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] Graph theory is the study of graphs, systems of nodes or vertices connected in pairs by lines or edges.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is the matching number of the graph, which equals the independence number of its line graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is the chromatic index of the graph, which equals the chromatic number of its line graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] of a graph is the maximum number of colors in a complete coloring.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] of an undirected graph is a proper coloring in which every two color classes induce a forest.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] The relation between two distinct edges that share an end vertex.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] In a graph with a matching, an alternating path is a path whose edges alternate between matched and unmatched edges.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] An alternating cycle is, similarly, a cycle whose edges alternate between matched and unmatched edges.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] An augmenting path is an alternating path that starts and ends at unsaturated vertices.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] of the matching and the augmenting path; a matching is maximum if and only if it has no augmenting path.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] A three-vertex independent set, the complement of a triangle.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] , a vertex adjacent to all other vertices.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] , although that term more properly refers to 2-ary trees in which the children of each node are distinguished as being left or right children (with at most one of each type).
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is a symmetry of a graph, an isomorphism from the graph to itself.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] A bipartite or multipartite graph is balanced if each two subsets of its vertex partition have sizes within one of each other.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] A ball (also known as a neighborhood ball or distance ball) is the set of all vertices that are at most distance r from a vertex.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] More formally, for a given vertex v and radius r, the ball B(v,r) consists of all vertices whose shortest path distance to v is less than or equal to r.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] , of the length of the longest edge (the number of steps in the ordering between its two endpoints).
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] The smallest possible ratio of the number of neighbors of a proper subset of vertices to the size of the subset.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is a graph whose vertices can be divided into two disjoint sets such that the vertices in one set are not connected to each other, but may be connected to vertices in the other set.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] Put another way, a bipartite graph is a graph with no odd cycles; equivalently, it is a graph that may be properly colored with two colors.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] are the subsets of vertices of each color.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] However, unless the graph is connected, it may not have a unique 2-coloring.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] graph in which there are only two different vertex degrees, one for each set of the vertex bipartition.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is a maximal subgraph which is either an isolated vertex, a bridge edge, or a 2-connected subgraph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] If a block is 2-connected, every pair of vertices in it belong to a common cycle.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] Every edge of a graph belongs in exactly one block.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is connected, its block-cutpoint graph is a tree.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] (also called a clique tree if connected, and sometimes erroneously called a Husimi tree) is a graph all of whose blocks are complete graphs.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is a block graph; so in particular the block graph of any graph is a block graph, and every block graph may be constructed as the block graph of a graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] : a set of edges whose removal disconnects the graph, for which no proper subset has the same property.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is an embedding of a graph onto a topological book, a space formed by joining a collection of half-planes along a shared line.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] Usually, the vertices of the embedding are required to be on the line, which is called the spine of the embedding, and the edges of the embedding are required to lie within a single half-plane, one of the pages of the book.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is a collection of mutually touching connected subgraphs, where two subgraphs touch if they share a vertex or each includes one endpoint of an edge.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] The order of a bramble is the smallest size of a set of vertices that has a nonempty intersection with all of the subgraphs.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] The treewidth of a graph is the maximum order of any of its brambles.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] A path of degree-two vertices, ending at vertices whose degree is unequal to two.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] , isthmus, or cut edge is an edge whose removal would disconnect the graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] A bridgeless graph is one that has no bridges; equivalently, a 2-edge-connected graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is a cycle with at most one bridge; it must be a face boundary in any planar embedding of its graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] A bridge of a cycle can also mean a path that connects two vertices of a cycle but is shorter than either of the paths in the cycle connecting the same two vertices.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is a graph in which every cycle of four or more vertices has a bridge.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] has five vertices and six edges; it is formed by two triangles that share a vertex.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] , cactus tree, cactus, or Husimi tree is a connected graph in which each edge belongs to at most one cycle.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] If, in addition, each vertex belongs to at most two blocks, then it is called a Christmas cactus.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is a regular graph with the smallest possible order for its girth.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] of a graph is an invariant such that two graphs have equal invariants if and only if they are isomorphic.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] Canonical forms may also be called canonical invariants or complete invariants, and are sometimes defined only for the graphs within a particular family of graphs.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is the process of computing a canonical form.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] Carving width is a notion of graph width analogous to branchwidth, but using hierarchical clusterings of vertices instead of hierarchical clusterings of edges.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] or caterpillar is a tree in which the internal nodes induce a path.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] , no other vertex has subtree size greater than half the size of the tree.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] , namely a set of vertices or a set of edges.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] along an outgoing edge, one that is directed away from the root.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is a graph in which every cycle of four or more vertices has a chord, so the only induced cycles are triangles.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is a chordal graph in which every cycle of length six or more has an odd chord.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is not chordal (unless it is a forest); it is a bipartite graph in which every cycle of six or more vertices has a chord, so the only induced cycles are 4-cycles.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] Chromatic graph theory is the theory of graph coloring.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] of a graph is the dimension of its cycle space.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] of a graph is the length of its longest simple cycle.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] The graph is Hamiltonian if and only if its circumference equals its order.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] of graphs or family of graphs is a (usually infinite) collection of graphs, often defined as the graphs having some specific property.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] The word "class" is used rather than "set" because, unless special restrictions are made (such as restricting the vertices to be drawn from a particular set, and defining edges to be sets of two vertices) classes of graphs are usually not sets when formalized using set theory.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] A color class of a colored graph is the set of vertices or edges having one particular color.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] , on edge coloring simple graphs, a graph is said to be of class one if its chromatic index equals its maximum degree, and class two if its chromatic index equals one plus the degree.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] According to Vizing's theorem, all simple graphs are either of class one or class two.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is a graph that does not have an induced subgraph that is a claw.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is a set of mutually adjacent vertices (or the complete subgraph induced by that set).
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] Sometimes a clique is defined as a maximal set of mutually adjacent vertices (or maximal complete subgraph), one that is not part of any larger such set (or subgraph).
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] by operations that create a labeled vertex, form the disjoint union of two labeled graphs, add an edge connecting all pairs of vertices with given labels, or relabel all vertices with a given label.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] A graph property is closed under some operation on graphs if, whenever the argument or arguments to the operation have the property, then so does the result.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] For instance, hereditary properties are closed under induced subgraphs; monotone properties are closed under subgraphs; and minor-closed properties are closed under minors.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] A closure of a directed graph is a set of vertices that have no outgoing edges to vertices outside the closure.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] For instance, a sink is a one-vertex closure.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is the problem of finding a closure of minimum or maximum weight.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is a coloring in which each vertex induces either an independent set (as in proper coloring) or a clique (as in a coloring of the complement).
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is a labeling of the vertices of a graph by elements from a given set of colors, or equivalently a partition of the vertices into subsets, called "color classes", each of which is associated with one of the colors.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] Some authors use "coloring", without qualification, to mean a proper coloring, one that assigns different colors to the endpoints of each edge.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] can be colored with at most four colors.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] It is so called because applying a greedy coloring algorithm to a degeneracy ordering of the graph uses at most this many colors.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] and two vertices are adjacent when they are comparable in the partial order.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] Equivalently, a comparability graph is a graph that has a transitive orientation.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] Many other classes of graphs can be defined as the comparability graphs of special types of partial order.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is one in which every two vertices are adjacent: all edges that could exist are present.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is one in which every two vertices on opposite sides of the partition of vertices are adjacent.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] A completion of a given graph is a supergraph that has some desired property.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is a supergraph that is a chordal graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is a proper coloring in which each pairs of colors is used for the endpoints of at least one edge.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] Every coloring with a minimum number of colors is complete, but there may exist complete colorings with larger numbers of colors.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] A complete invariant of a graph is a synonym for a canonical form, an invariant that has different values for non-isomorphic graphs.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] of a graph is a maximal connected subgraph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is one in which each pair of vertices forms the endpoints of a path.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is an elementary operation that removes an edge from a graph while merging the two vertices that it previously joined.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] Vertex contraction (sometimes called vertex identification) is similar, but the two vertices are not necessarily connected by an edge.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] Path contraction occurs upon the set of edges in a path that contract to form a single edge between the endpoints of the path.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] The inverse of edge contraction is vertex splitting.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] , and is a core in the sense that all of its self-homomorphisms are isomorphisms.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] , formed as the union of all maximum matchings.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] , in which each cograph vertex is a leaf of the tree, each internal node of the tree is labeled with 0 or 1, and two cograph vertices are adjacent if and only if their lowest common ancestor in the tree is labeled 1.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is a set of vertices incident to every edge in a graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is a set of edges incident to every vertex in a graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] – taken vertex-wise and edge-wise – is equal to the graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] A critical graph for a given property is a graph that has the property but such that every subgraph formed by deleting a single vertex does not have the property.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is one that has a perfect matching (a 1-factor) for every vertex deletion, but (because it has an odd number of vertices) has no perfect matching itself.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] , used for graphs which do not have a property but for which every one-vertex deletion does.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] , the eight-vertex graph of the vertices and edges of a cube.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] , a higher-dimensional generalization of the cube graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] , formed from a hypercube by adding a matching connecting opposite vertices.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] , a distance-preserving subgraph of a hypercube.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] , a cubic graph formed by replacing each vertex of a hypercube by a cycle.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is a partition of the vertices of a graph into two subsets, or the set (also known as a cut-set) of edges that span such a partition, if that set is non-empty.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] An edge is said to span the partition if it has endpoints in both subsets.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] Thus, the removal of a cut-set from a connected graph disconnects it.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] of sets as its vector addition operation.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] ) or more usually a closed walk without repeated vertices and consequently edges (also called a simple cycle).
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] and reversals of the walk produce the same cycle.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] generated by the simple cycles in a graph, often over the field of 2 elements but also over other fields.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] , a directed graph without any directed cycles.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] An edge-deck is formed in the same way by deleting a single edge in all possible ways.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] (graphs that do not have a property that is held by all cards).
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] of a vertex in a graph is its number of incident edges.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is the collection of degrees of all vertices, in sorted order from largest to smallest.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] In a directed graph, one may distinguish the in-degree (number of incoming edges) and out-degree (number of outgoing edges).
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] , the order of the largest clique minor.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] The depth of a node in a rooted tree is the number of edges in the path from the root to the node.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] For instance, the depth of the root is 0 and the depth of any one of its adjacent nodes is 1.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] That is, it is the maximum of the distances between pairs of vertices in the graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] If the graph has weights on its edges, then its weighted diameter measures path length by the sum of the edge weights along a path, while the unweighted diameter measures path length by the number of edges.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] For disconnected graphs, definitions vary: the diameter may be defined as infinite, or as the largest diameter of a connected component, or it may be undefined.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is an undirected graph with four vertices and five edges.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is a simple cycle of length two in a directed graph or a multigraph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] The tail of a directed edge whose head is the given vertex.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] The head of a directed edge whose tail is the given vertex.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is one in which the edges have a distinguished direction, from one vertex to another.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] , a directed edge is again one that has a distinguished direction; directed edges may also be called arcs or arrows.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] between any two vertices in a graph is the length of the shortest path having the two vertices as its endpoints.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] A domatic partition of a graph is a partition of the vertices into dominating sets.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] of the graph is the maximum number of dominating sets in such a partition.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is a set of vertices that includes or is adjacent to every vertex in the graph; not to be confused with a vertex cover, a vertex set that is incident to all edges in the graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] Important special types of dominating sets include independent dominating sets (dominating sets that are also independent sets) and connected dominating sets (dominating sets that induced connected subgraphs).
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] A single-vertex dominating set may also be called a universal vertex.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] The domination number of a graph is the number of vertices in the smallest dominating set.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] An ear of a graph is a path whose endpoints may coincide but in which otherwise there are no repetitions of vertices or edges.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is a partition of the edges of a graph into a sequence of ears, each of whose endpoints (after the first one) belong to a previous ear and each of whose interior points do not belong to any previous ear.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] An open ear is a simple path (an ear without repeated vertices), and an open ear decomposition is an ear decomposition in which each ear after the first is open; a graph has an open ear decomposition if and only if it is biconnected.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] An ear is odd if it has an odd number of edges, and an odd ear decomposition is an ear decomposition in which each ear is odd; a graph has an odd ear decomposition if and only if it is factor-critical.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] The eccentricity of a vertex is the farthest distance from it to any other vertex.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] An edge is (together with vertices) one of the two basic units out of which graphs are constructed.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] Each edge has two (or in hypergraphs, more) vertices to which it is attached, called its endpoints.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] Edges may be directed or undirected; undirected edges are also called lines and directed edges are also called arcs or arrows.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] , an edge may be represented as the set of its vertices, and in a directed simple graph it may be represented as an ordered pair of its vertices.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] or totally disconnected graph on a given set of vertices is the graph that has no edges.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] It is sometimes called the empty graph, but this term can also refer to a graph with no vertices.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is a topological representation of a graph as a subset of a topological space with each vertex represented as a point, each edge represented as a curve having the endpoints of the edge as endpoints of the curve, and no other intersections between vertices or edges.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is a graph that has such an embedding onto a torus.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] , a graph with no vertices and no edges.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] of an infinite graph is an equivalence class of rays, where two rays are equivalent if there is a third ray that includes infinitely many vertices from both of them.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] One of the two vertices joined by a given edge, or one of the first or last vertex of a walk, trail or path.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is the problem of counting the graphs in a given class of graphs, as a function of their order.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] More generally, enumeration problems can refer either to problems of counting a certain class of combinatorial objects (such as cliques, independent sets, colorings, or spanning trees), or of algorithmically listing all such objects.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is a walk that uses every edge of a graph exactly once.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] An Eulerian circuit (also called an Eulerian cycle or an Euler tour) is a closed walk that uses every edge exactly once.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] An Eulerian graph is a graph that has an Eulerian circuit.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] For an undirected graph, this means that the graph is connected and every vertex has even degree.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] For a directed graph, this means that the graph is strongly connected and every vertex has in-degree equal to the out-degree.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] In some cases, the connectivity requirement is loosened, and a graph meeting only the degree requirements is called Eulerian.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] Divisible by two; for instance, an even cycle is a cycle whose length is even.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is a graph whose edge expansion, vertex expansion, or spectral expansion is bounded away from zero.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] of its adjacency matrix and the second-largest eigenvalue.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] , a connected component of the subset of the plane or surface of the embedding that is disjoint from the graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] For an embedding in the plane, all but one face will be bounded; the one exceptional face that extends to infinity is called the outer (or infinite) face.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] A factor of a graph is a spanning subgraph: a subgraph that includes all of the vertices of the graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] A graph is finite if it has a finite number of vertices and a finite number of edges.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] Many sources assume that all graphs are finite without explicitly saying so.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] A graph is locally finite if each vertex has a finite number of incident edges.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] An infinite graph is a graph that is not finite: it has infinitely many vertices, infinitely many edges, or both.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is a form of logic in which variables represent vertices of a graph, and there exists a binary predicate to test whether two vertices are adjacent.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] To be distinguished from second order logic, in which variables can also represent sets of vertices or edges.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] , functions that map small sets of vertices to their flaps.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] of a cycle, which is either a flap of the cycle vertices or a chord of the cycle.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is a characterization of a family of graphs as being the graphs that do not have certain other graphs as subgraphs, induced subgraphs, or minors.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is an undirected graph without cycles (a disjoint union of unrooted trees), or a directed graph formed as a disjoint union of rooted trees.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] , one of the two smallest cubic graphs with no nontrivial symmetries.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] that every finite group is the group of symmetries of a finite graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] is a directed graph where every vertex has out-degree one.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] Equivalently, a functional graph is a maximal directed pseudoforest.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] A variable often used to denote a graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] When used as an adjective, it means related to shortest paths or shortest path distances.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] , a giant component is a connected component that contains a constant fraction of the vertices of the graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] In standard models of random graphs, there is typically at most one giant component.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] of a graph is the length of its shortest cycle.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] The fundamental object of study in graph theory, a system of vertices connected in pairs by edges.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] according to whether the edges have an orientation or not.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] of a graph is a coloring produced by considering the vertices in some sequence and assigning each vertex the first available color.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] , the smallest triangle-free graph requiring four colors in any proper coloring.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p01] that triangle-free planar graphs can always be colored with at most three colors.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] of a graph is the order of the largest complete minor of the graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] It is also called the contraction clique number or the homomorphism degree.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is the conjecture that the Hadwiger number is never less than the chromatic number.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] or Hamiltonian cycle is a simple spanning path or simple spanning cycle: it covers all of the vertices in the graph exactly once.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A graph is Hamiltonian if it contains a Hamiltonian cycle, and traceable if it contains a Hamiltonian path.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] vertices to one of its flaps, often satisfying additional consistency conditions.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] Havens can be used to characterize the treewidth of finite graphs and the ends and Hadwiger numbers of infinite graphs.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] of a node in a rooted tree is the number of edges in a longest path, going away from the root (i.e. its nodes have strictly increasing depth), that starts at that node and ends at a leaf.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] of a rooted tree is the height of its root.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] of a tree is the number of edges in a longest possible path, going away from the root, that starts at the root and ends at a leaf.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is the maximum length of a directed path in this graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A simple cycle consisting of exactly six edges and six vertices.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A hole is an induced cycle of length four or more.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] An anti-hole is an induced subgraph of order four whose complement is a cycle; equivalently, it is a hole in the complement graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] as being the graphs with no odd holes or odd anti-holes.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] if there exist two homomorphisms, one from each graph to the other graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a mapping from the vertex set of one graph to the vertex set of another graph that maps adjacent vertices to adjacent vertices.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] This type of mapping between graphs is the one that is most commonly used in category-theoretic approaches to graph theory.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A proper graph coloring can equivalently be described as a homomorphism to a complete graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] , having any number of endpoints, in contrast to the requirement that edges of graphs have exactly two endpoints.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a generalization of a graph in which each edge (called a hyperedge in this context) may have more than two endpoints.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] This prefix, in combination with a graph property, indicates a graph that does not have the property but such that every subgraph formed by deleting a single vertex does have the property.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is one that does not have a Hamiltonian cycle, but for which every one-vertex deletion produces a Hamiltonian subgraph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] , used for graphs which have a property but for which every one-vertex deletion does not.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] in a graph is a vertex-edge pair such that the vertex is an endpoint of the edge.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] (Adjective) The relation between an edge and one of its endpoints.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a set of vertices that induces an edgeless subgraph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] It may also be called a stable set or a coclique.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] of a graph, a subset of edges is independent if the corresponding subgraph is a tree or forest.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] or full subgraph of a graph is a subgraph formed from a subset of vertices and from all of the edges that have both endpoints in the subset.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] , induced subgraphs that are paths or cycles.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A vertex of a path or tree is internal if it is not a leaf; that is, if its degree is greater than one.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] ) if they do not have any vertex in common, except the first and last ones.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a graph whose vertices correspond to sets or geometric objects, with an edge between two vertices exactly when the corresponding two sets or objects have a nonempty intersection.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] (intersection graphs of the maximal cliques of a graph).
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] Every graph is an intersection graph for some family of sets, and this family is called an intersection representation of the graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] An isolated vertex of a graph is a vertex whose degree is zero, that is, a vertex with no incident edges.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a one-to-one incidence preserving correspondence of the vertices and edges of one graph to the vertices and edges of another graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] Two graphs related in this way are said to be isomorphic.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] , in the sense of an edge whose removal disconnects the graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] by adding an edge from each vertex of one graph to each vertex of the other.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] Equivalently, it is the complement of the disjoint union of the complements.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] may be used to specify which objects of a graph have labels.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] refers to several different problems of assigning labels to graphs subject to certain constraints.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] , in which the labels are interpreted as colors.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] , the vertices of a graph are said to be labeled if they are all distinguishable from each other.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] For instance, this can be made to be true by fixing a one-to-one correspondence between the vertices and the integers from 1 to the order of the graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] When vertices are labeled, graphs that are isomorphic to each other (but with different vertex orderings) are counted as separate objects.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] In contrast, when the vertices are unlabeled, graphs that are isomorphic to each other are not counted separately.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A leaf edge or pendant edge is the edge connecting a leaf vertex to its single neighbour.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] of a tree is a graph whose vertices are the leaves of the tree and whose edges connect leaves whose distance in the tree is at most a given threshold.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] In an unweighted graph, the length of a cycle, path, or walk is the number of edges it uses.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] In a weighted graph, it may instead be the sum of the weights of the edges that it uses.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A node's level in a rooted tree is the number of nodes in the path from the root to the node.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] For instance, the root has level 1 and any one of its adjacent nodes has level 2.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A set of all node having the same level or depth.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a computer representation of graphs for use in graph algorithms.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a variation of graph coloring in which each vertex has a list of available colors.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] For instance, a graph is locally finite if all of its neighborhoods are finite.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] or self-loop is an edge both of whose endpoints are the same vertex.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a set of edges in which no two share any vertex.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A vertex is matched or saturated if it is one of the endpoints of an edge in the matching.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] or complete matching is a matching that matches every vertex; it may also be called a 1-factor, and can only exist when the order is even.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A near-perfect matching, in a graph with odd order, is one that saturates all but one vertex.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is the number of edges in a maximum matching.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a matching to which no additional edges can be added.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a complete subgraph that cannot be expanded to a larger complete subgraph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] The word "maximal" should be distinguished from "maximum": a maximum subgraph is always maximal, but not necessarily vice versa.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A simple graph with a given property is maximal for that property if it is not possible to add any more edges to it (keeping the vertex set unchanged) while preserving both the simplicity of the graph and the property.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a planar graph such that adding any more edges to it would create a non-planar graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is maximum for a particular property if it is the largest subgraph (by order or size) among all subgraphs with that property.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is any of the largest cliques in a given graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a graph in which every three vertices have a unique median.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a graph in which every odd cycle of length five or more has at least two chords.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A subgraph of given graph is minimal for a particular property if it has that property but no proper subgraph of it also has the same property.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a graph that may include both directed and undirected edges.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] , a graph in which each triple of vertices has at least one median vertex that belongs to shortest paths between all pairs of the triple.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] , a decomposition of a graph into subgraphs within which all vertices connect to the rest of the graph in the same way.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] of a graph clustering, the difference of the number of cross-cluster edges from its expected value.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a regular graph for which the Moore bound is met exactly.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a graph that allows multiple adjacencies (and, often, self-loops); a graph that is not required to be simple.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A multiple adjacency or multiple edge is a set of more than one edge that all have the same endpoints (in the same direction, in the case of directed graphs).
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A graph with multiple edges is often called a multigraph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] The multiplicity of an edge is the number of edges in a multiple adjacency.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] The multiplicity of a graph is the maximum multiplicity of any of its edges.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is often used (especially in computer science) to denote the number of vertices in a given graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A vertex that is adjacent to a given vertex.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] When the openness or closedness of a neighborhood is not specified, it is assumed to be open.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A graph in which attributes (e.g. names) are associated with the nodes and/or edges.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A non-edge or anti-edge is a pair of vertices that are not adjacent; the edges of the complement graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] of a non-bipartite graph is the length of its shortest odd cycle.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] An odd hole is a special case of an odd cycle: one that is induced and has four or more vertices.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] An odd vertex is a vertex whose degree is odd.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] every finite undirected graph has an even number of odd vertices.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] An odd chord is an edge connecting two vertices that are an odd distance apart in an even cycle.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] (an order in which each vertex has minimum degree in the induced subgraph of it and all later vertices).
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] of an undirected graph is an assignment of directions to its edges, making it into a directed graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] An oriented graph is one that has been assigned an orientation.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is an oriented tree; it differs from a directed tree (an arborescence) in that there is no requirement of consistency in the directions of its edges.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] , orientations that are transitively closed.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a graph that can be embedded in the plane (without crossings) so that all vertices are on the outer face of the graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] along the incoming edge, the one that is directed toward the root.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] may either be a walk or a walk without repeated vertices and consequently edges (also called a simple path), depending on the source.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a tree decomposition whose underlying tree is a path.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] Its width is defined in the same way as for tree decompositions, as one less than the size of the largest bag.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] It is also known as interval thickness, vertex separation number, or node searching number.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a graph in which, in every induced subgraph, the chromatic number equals the clique number.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] are two theorems about perfect graphs, the former proving that their complements are also perfect and the latter proving that they are exactly the graphs with no odd holes or anti-holes.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a graph whose vertices can be ordered in such a way that a greedy coloring algorithm with this ordering optimally colors every induced subgraph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] The perfectly orderable graphs are a subclass of the perfect graphs.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a partition of the edges of a graph into perfect matchings so that each two matchings form a Hamiltonian cycle.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] or non-separating cycle is a cycle with at most one bridge.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] , a 10-vertex 15-edge graph frequently used as a counterexample.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] that every bridgeless cubic graph has a perfect matching.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A plane graph is a planar graph for which a particular embedding has already been fixed.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is an oriented tree; equivalently, a directed acyclic graph whose underlying undirected graph is a tree.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a closely related concept, derived from a power of a tree by taking the subgraph induced by the tree's leaves.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a method for analyzing complex networks by identifying cliques, bicliques, and stars within the network.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] are a phenomenon in which the number of vertices of a given degree is proportional to a power of the degree.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] , a prime graph is a graph without any nontrivial modules.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] , cuts whose cut-set is a complete bipartite graph, a prime graph is a graph without any splits.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] Every quotient graph of a maximal decomposition by splits is a prime graph, a star, or a complete graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a connected graph that is not itself a product.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] Every connected graph can be uniquely factored into a Cartesian product of prime graphs.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] or proper circular arc graph is an intersection graph of a collection of intervals or circular arcs (respectively) such that no interval or arc contains another interval or arc.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] Proper interval graphs are also called unit interval graphs (because they can always be represented by unit intervals) or indifference graphs.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is something that can be true of some graphs and false of others, and that depends only on the graph structure and not on incidental information such as labels.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] Graph properties may equivalently be described in terms of classes of graphs (the graphs that have a given property).
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] More generally, a graph property may also be a function of graphs that is again independent of incidental information, such as the size, order, or degree sequence of a graph; this more general definition of a property is also called an invariant of the graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is an undirected graph in which each connected component has at most one cycle, or a directed graph in which each vertex has at most one outgoing edge.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A pseudograph is a graph or multigraph that allows self-loops.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A quasi-line graph or locally co-bipartite graph is a graph in which the open neighborhood of every vertex can be partitioned into two cliques.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] They are used in the structure theory of claw-free graphs.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] The edges of a quiver are called arrows.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a graph whose spectral expansion is as large as possible.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A ray, in an infinite graph, is an infinite simple path with exactly one endpoint.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] of a graph are equivalence classes of rays.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] , a graph property is recognizable if its truth can be determined from the deck of the graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] Many graph properties are known to be recognizable.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] If the reconstruction conjecture is true, all graph properties are recognizable.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] In this context, reconstruction is the formation of a graph from its deck.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A simple cycle consisting of exactly four edges and four vertices.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A regular tournament is a tournament where in-degree equals out-degree for all vertices.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a form of logic in which variables may represent vertices, edges, sets of vertices, and (sometimes) sets of edges.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] This logic includes predicates for testing whether a vertex and edge are incident, as well as whether a vertex or edge belongs to a set.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] To be distinguished from first order logic, in which variables can only represent vertices.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a graph without loops and without multiple adjacencies.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] That is, each edge connects two distinct endpoints and no two edges have the same endpoints.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A simple edge is an edge that is not part of a multiple adjacency.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] In many cases, graphs are assumed to be simple unless specified otherwise.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A simple path or a simple cycle is a path or cycle that has no repeated vertices and consequently no repeated edges.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A sink, in a directed graph, is a vertex with no outgoing edges (out-degree equals 0).
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a graph in which most nodes are not neighbors of one another, but most nodes can be reached from every other node by a small number of hops or steps.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a simple, connected, bridgeless cubic graph with chromatic index equal to 4.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A source, in a directed graph, is a vertex with no incoming edges (in-degree equals 0).
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a subspace of the edge space that has the cut-sets of the graph as its elements.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] has the Eulerian spanning subgraphs as its elements.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A spanner is a (usually sparse) graph whose shortest path distances approximate those in a dense graph or other metric space.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] , spanning trees of a graph whose distances approximate the graph distances, and graph spanners, sparse subgraphs of a dense graph whose distances approximate the original graph's distances.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A greedy spanner is a graph spanner constructed by a greedy algorithm, generally one that considers all edges from shortest to longest and keeps the ones that are needed to preserve the distance approximation.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A subgraph is spanning when it includes all of the vertices of the given graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] (spanning subgraphs that are matchings).
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] , especially (but not only) when it is regular.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is one that has few edges relative to its number of vertices.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] In some definitions the same property should also be true for all subgraphs of the given graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is the branch of graph theory that uses spectra to analyze graphs.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a graph whose vertices can be partitioned into a clique and an independent set.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A related class of graphs, the double split graphs, are used in the proof of the strong perfect graph theorem.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] of an arbitrary graph is a partition of its vertices into two nonempty subsets, such that the edges spanning this cut form a complete bipartite subgraph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A split is called a strong split when it is not crossed by any other split.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A split is called nontrivial when both of its sides have more than one vertex.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A graph is called prime when it has no nontrivial splits.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] (sometimes called vertex cleaving) is an elementary graph operation that splits a vertex into two, where these two new vertices are adjacent to the vertices that the original vertex was adjacent to.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] The inverse of vertex splitting is vertex contraction.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] of a bipartite graph is the subgraph of its square induced by one side of the bipartition.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a planar graph that can be drawn so that all bounded faces are 4-cycles and all vertices of degree ≤ 3 belong to the outer face.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] defined from points in the plane with integer coordinates connected by unit-length edges.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] The special case of a star with three leaves is called a claw.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is the minimum ratio of the number of edges removed from the graph to components created, over all possible removals; it is analogous to toughness, based on vertex removals.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a regular graph in which every two adjacent vertices have the same number of shared neighbours and every two non-adjacent vertices have the same number of shared neighbours.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a chordal graph in which every even cycle of length six or more has an odd chord.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A strongly perfect graph is a graph in which every induced subgraph has an independent set meeting all maximal cliques.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] are also called "very strongly perfect graphs" because in them, every vertex belongs to such an independent set.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] The vertex subset must include all endpoints of the edge subset, but may also include additional vertices.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is one that includes all the edges whose endpoints belong to the vertex subset.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A subtree is a connected subgraph of a tree.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] Sometimes, for rooted trees, subtrees are defined to be a special type of connected subgraph, formed by all vertices and edges reachable from a chosen vertex.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A graph formed by adding vertices, edges, or both to a given graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] of a collection of points in the Euclidean plane is constructed by constructing a system of cones surrounding each point and adding one edge per cone, to the point whose projection onto a central ray of the cone is smallest.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] or Lovász theta function of a graph is a graph invariant related to the clique number and chromatic number that can be computed in polynomial time by semidefinite programming.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a representation of the vertices and edges of a graph by points and curves in the plane (not necessarily avoiding crossings).
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is the algorithmic problem of arranging a directed acyclic graph into a topological order, a vertex sequence such that each edge goes from an earlier vertex to a later vertex in the sequence.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] that starts and ends at the same vertex and has no repeated edges.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is an orientation of a complete graph; that is, it is a directed graph such that every two vertices are connected by exactly one directed edge (going in only one of the two directions between the two vertices).
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a graph that contains a Hamiltonian path.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] of a given directed graph is a graph on the same vertex set that has an edge from one vertex to another whenever the original graph has a path connecting the same two vertices.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] of a graph is a minimal graph having the same transitive closure; directed acyclic graphs have a unique transitive reduction.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] of a given directed graph is a graph on the same vertices, with each edge reversed in direction.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] It may also be called the converse or reverse of the graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is an undirected graph that is both connected and acyclic, or a directed graph in which there exists a unique walk from one vertex (the root of the tree) to all remaining vertices.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is an undirected graph that does not have any triangle subgraphs.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A trivial graph is a graph with 0 or 1 vertices.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a balanced complete multipartite graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] states that Turán graphs have the maximum number of edges among all clique-free graphs of a given order.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] asks for the minimum number of crossings in a drawing of a complete bipartite graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] In a rooted tree, a unary vertex is a vertex which has exactly one child vertex.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a graph in which the two endpoints of each edge are not distinguished from each other.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] , an undirected edge is again one in which the endpoints are not distinguished from each other.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a graph that contains as subgraphs all graphs in a given family of graphs, or all graphs of a given size or order within a given family of graphs.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] (also called an apex or dominating vertex) is a vertex that is adjacent to every other vertex in the graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] in a formula may be called a universal vertex for that formula.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] (plural vertices) is (together with edges) one of the two basic units out of which graphs are constructed.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] Vertices of graphs are often considered to be atomic objects, with no internal structure.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] that the chromatic index is at most one more than the maximum degree.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] on the domination number of Cartesian products of graphs.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] The sum of the degrees of a set of vertices.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] characterizing planar graphs by their forbidden minors.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] graph is called weakly connected if replacing all of its directed edges with undirected edges produces a connected (undirected) graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A numerical value, assigned as a label to a vertex or edge of a graph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] The weight of a subgraph is the sum of the weights of the vertices or edges within that subgraph.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] A vertex-weighted graph has weights on its vertices and an edge-weighted graph has weights on its edges.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is a graph all of whose maximal independent sets are the same size.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] The width of a tree decomposition or path decomposition is one less than the maximum size of one of its bags, and may be used to define treewidth and pathwidth.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is the maximum cardinality of an antichain.
[src:hierholzer/glossary-of-graph-theory-p02] is the union of a collection of cliques, all of the same order as each other, with one shared vertex belonging to all the cliques and all other vertices and edges distinct.
[src:hierholzer/multigraph] In mathematics, and more specifically in graph theory, a **multigraph** is a graph which is permitted to have multiple edges (also called *parallel edges*), that is, edges that have the same end nodes.
[src:hierholzer/multigraph] Thus two vertices may be connected by more than one edge.
[src:hierholzer/multigraph] A multigraph is different from a hypergraph, which is a graph in which an edge can connect any number of nodes, not just two.
[src:hierholzer/multigraph] For some authors, the terms *pseudograph* and *multigraph* are synonymous.
[src:hierholzer/multigraph] For others, a **pseudograph** is a multigraph that is permitted to have loops.
[src:hierholzer/multigraph] Some authors allow multigraphs to have loops, that is, an edge that connects a vertex to itself, while others call these **pseudographs**, reserving the term multigraph for the case with no loops.
[src:hierholzer/multigraph] A **multidigraph** is a directed graph which is permitted to have *multiple arcs,* i.e., arcs with the same source and target nodes.
[src:hierholzer/multigraph] A **mixed multigraph** *G* := (*V*, *E*, *A*) may be defined in the same way as a mixed graph.
[src:hierholzer/multigraph] This notion might be used to model the possible flight connections offered by an airline.
[src:hierholzer/multigraph] In this case the multigraph would be a directed graph with pairs of directed parallel edges connecting cities to show that it is possible to fly both *to* and *from* these locations.
[src:hierholzer/multigraph] In category theory a small category can be defined as a multidigraph (with edges having their own identity) equipped with an associative composition law and a distinguished self-loop at each vertex serving as the left and right identity for composition.
[src:hierholzer/multigraph] For this reason, in category theory the term *graph* is standardly taken to mean "multidigraph", and the underlying multidigraph of a category is called its **underlying digraph**.
[src:hierholzer/multigraph] Multigraphs and multidigraphs also support the notion of graph labeling, in a similar way.
[src:hierholzer/multigraph] However, there is no unity in terminology in this case.
[src:hierholzer/multigraph] The definitions of **labeled multigraphs** and **labeled multidigraphs** are similar, and we define only the latter ones here.
[src:hierholzer/multigraph] Formally: A labeled multidigraph G is a multigraph with *labeled* vertices and arcs.
